To fix disk space error in jenkins


Step 1 — Open fstab again
Run:

sudo nano /etc/fstab

You’ll see some existing lines.


Do NOT edit the first lines.

Your file should look similar to this (example):

UUID=xxxx-xxxx  /        xfs   defaults,noatime  0 1
UUID=xxxx-xxxx  /boot    xfs   defaults          0 2

Step 2 — Fix the mistake
You likely added the tmpfs line at the top or broke spacing.
Scroll to the very bottom and add the line exactly like this:

tmpfs   /tmp    tmpfs   defaults,size=2G   0 0

Important:
	• Each column must be separated by spaces or tabs
	• The line must be at the bottom
	• There must be no extra characters

Your final file should look like:
UUID=xxxx-xxxx  /        xfs   defaults,noatime  0 1
UUID=xxxx-xxxx  /boot    xfs   defaults          0 2
tmpfs   /tmp    tmpfs   defaults,size=2G   0 0

Save:
CTRL + O → Enter → CTRL + X


Step 3 — Test fstab safely
Before remounting, run:
sudo mount -a
If no error appears, the file is fixed ✅
If you still see error, paste your fstab here and I’ll correct it.

Step 4 — Remount /tmp
sudo mount -o remount /tmp
df -h /tmp
You should now see ~2.0G.

Step 5 — Restart Jenkins
sudo systemctl restart jenkins
Refresh Jenkins → node should become ONLINE 🎉

Run sudo mount -a and tell me if it shows any error.


