OPTION 2


Perfect — you’ve found the root cause 🎯
Jenkins automatically puts the node offline when disk space is low to protect the server.
Message means:
Disk space below threshold (1 GB)
Only 452 MB left
So Jenkins refuses to run builds to avoid crashing your EC2.
We need to free space.

Step 1 — Check what is using space
Run this on EC2:
df -h
You will likely see / almost full (common on t2.micro).

Step 2 — Clean package cache (big win)
Run:
sudo dnf clean all

Step 3 — Remove old Jenkins build cache
Jenkins stores logs + old builds here:
sudo du -sh /var/lib/jenkins/*
Now clean workspace + old builds:
sudo rm -rf /var/lib/jenkins/workspace/*
sudo rm -rf /var/lib/jenkins/jobs/*/builds/*
This alone usually frees 1–2 GB.

Step 4 — Clean system logs
Logs grow very fast on Amazon Linux:
sudo journalctl --vacuum-time=1d

Step 5 — Clean temp files
sudo rm -rf /tmp/*

Step 6 — Verify free space
df -h
You should now have >1 GB free.

Step 7 — Restart Jenkins
sudo systemctl restart jenkins
Refresh Jenkins → Node should become ONLINE automatically.

Important tip for t2.micro users 💡
Jenkins + Maven needs more disk.
If this keeps happening, increase EBS disk from 8GB → 20GB (takes 2 minutes in AWS console).

Run the cleanup commands and tell me how much free space you now have 👍
